{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588886"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15199"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15199"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68519"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7890"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68519"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is examining kidney stones collected from several patients. The stones vary in their physical appearance and radiological characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical appearance of uric acid stones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Black and crystalline","Yellow-brown and smooth","Red and striated","White and spiculated","Green and granular"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EKidney stones have distinct appearances that help in their identification and management:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow-brown and smooth\u003C/strong\u003E stones are characteristic of uric acid stones. These stones are radiolucent on plain radiographs and typically form in acidic urine with pH less than 5.5.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlack and crystalline\u003C/strong\u003E appearance is not typical of any common kidney stone type.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed and striated\u003C/strong\u003E appearance is not typical of any common kidney stone type.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite and spiculated\u003C/strong\u003E appearance is more typical of calcium oxalate stones, which are radio-opaque.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreen and granular\u003C/strong\u003E appearance is not characteristic of any common kidney stone type.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the physical characteristics of kidney stones is important as it helps guide treatment and prevention strategies. Uric acid stones can often be managed with urinary alkalinisation, while other stone types may require different approaches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Uric acid kidney stones are radiolucent, smooth, yellow-brown in colour, and often form in acidic urine.","Different types of kidney stones have distinct physical and radiological characteristics that aid in diagnosis and management.","Uric acid stones can be managed with urinary alkalinisation due to their pH-dependent formation."],"references":["Khan SR, Pearle MS, Robertson WG, Gambaro G, Canales BK, Doizi S, Traxer O, Tiselius HG. Kidney stones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Feb 25;2:16008. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.8. PMID: 27188687; PMCID: PMC5685519","Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Murphy PB. Renal Calculi, Nephrolithiasis. [Updated 2024 Apr 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442014/","stroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences. Fontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Apr 15;99(8):490-496. PMID: 30990297","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15199"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T19:54:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T19:55:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7890"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68519"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag